    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Geological Society, | Burlington House, W.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>9 May 1879</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>Have you seen a small work just published by Hardwicke &amp; Bogue, entitled “Evolution, old &amp; new” by Samuel Butler? I have read but a little way in it, but the author seems to be writing the panegyric of D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Erasmus Darwin &amp; his Philosophy—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> There are over 20 pages of the life of D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Darwin &amp; 40 of exposition of his views &amp; quotations from the “Zoonomia”.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Does not this rather take the wind out of our sails?</p>
<p>Believe me | yours very truly | W. S. Dallas <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">C. Darwin Esq G</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
          
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_774.xml">Samuel Butler</ref> discussed <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1219.xml">Erasmus Darwin</ref>, CD’s grandfather, in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10523.xml">S. Butler 1879</ref>, pp. 173–234. Dallas was translating <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2758.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst Krause’s</ref> revised essay on Erasmus Darwin (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10668.xml">Krause 1879a</ref>) for publication as part of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2365.xml"><hi rend="italic">Erasmus Darwin</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Erasmus Darwin had published his evolutionary views in <hi rend="italic">Zoonomia</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1791.xml">E. Darwin 1794–6</ref>).</note> 
        </div>
    
